name: 6-[bis(5-ethylfuran-2-yl)methyl]-7-nitro-2,3-dihydro-1,4-benzodioxine
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-2671
Reason: 6-[bis(5-ethylfuran-2-yl)methyl]-7-nitro-2,3-dihydro-1,4-benzodioxine has a complex structure with multiple functional groups, which will impact its melting point. Starting with the basic unit of benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 °C, we have substantial structural components to consider. The molecular structure includes two furan rings, which typically increase the melting point due to increased molecular rigidity and pi-stacking interactions; this effect is estimated to add about +25 °C for each additional fused ring. The ethyl group can also contribute to the melting point due to its ability to participate in hydrogen bonding, estimated at around +5 °C. The nitro group introduces a strong dipole moment, which can increase the melting point due to stronger intermolecular interactions, estimated at around +10 °C. The dioxane-like bridging moiety can also contribute to the melting point due to its rigidity and potential hydrogen bonding, estimated at around +5 °C.
